value.value: A surgical procedure to remove any cancerous tissue in the esophagus.
A test to determine the strength and muscle coordination of the esophagus. This is measured by pressure sensors in a small catheter that is inserted into the esophagus.
A surgical procedure to remove part of the esophagus.
Eye evisceration is the removal of the contents of the eye, leaving the eye muscles and the sclera. Enucleation is the removal of the entire eye.
The remaking or remodeling of the bones that provide a framework for the eye. The actual methods are dependent on the cause.
The application of medication to increase the fullness of eyelashes.
A type of surgery that repairs droopy eyelids and may involve removing excessive tissue, fat and muscle from the area.
A surgical procedure to remodel the eyelid for cosmetic reasons or to treat an eyelid defect.
A surgical procedure to remove excess skin from the face to create a more youthful appearance.
The insertion of implantable material into the face to restore a more youthful appearance or correct a facial deformity.
Surgery to the face with the intent of making the face more aesthetically pleasing.
A surgical procedure to treat a diseased femoral artery in which a section of another blood vessel is sewn to the femoral artery to bypass the diseased area.

Ablation of an irritable area of the heart that is the source of atrial fibrillation with the technology Focal Impulse and Rotor Modulation (FIRM), which is a mapping technology to precisely identify the area of trouble.
A surgical procedure to repair a pathologic communication between two areas that should not be communicating.
A plastic surgery procedure in which excess skin is removed from the forehead to create a more youthful appearance.
Actual observation and treatment of disease in patients (including experimental treatment) as distinct from theoretical or experimental work.
An injection of local anesthetics to the bundle of nerves supplying sensation to the face and scalp. This may provide relief from facial pain associated with facial pain syndromes or cancer pain.
Surgery on the stomach to aid in the treatment of an esophageal disorder.
Abdominal implantation in the abdomen of a device that sends mild electrical impulses to the nerves and muscles of the lower stomach as a treatment for nausea and vomiting.

A device that is implanted under the skin and has electrodes that attach to the stomach. This device is programmed to stimulate the stomach to empty, which is a problem in individuals with gastroparesis.
A procedure to insert a tube for feeding into the stomach.
Surgery to treat a glioma, glioblastoma or astrocytoma.
A diet that excludes gluten.
Meningitis that is attributed to the bacteria H influenze type B.
Pneumonia that is attributed to the bacteria H influenze type B.
Removal of body hair.

The detailed planning of studies of the safety, efficacy, or optimum dosage schedule (if appropriate) of one or more diagnostic, therapeutic, or prophylactic drugs, devices, or techniques selected according to predetermined criteria of eligibility and observed for predefined evidence of favorable and unfavorable effects.
Replacement of hair, usually on the head.
Surgery on the head or neck to treat cancer.
Devices that are used to enhance hearing.
Surgical incision made in the esophageal sphincter to allow easier passage of food and liquids into the stomach.
Treatment to cure a hepatitis C infection. Antiviral therapy is prescribed based on the hepatitis C genotype, co-existing medical conditions and prior treatments.
The use of an arthroscope to visualize the joint of the hip.
A surgical procedure to replace part or all of a hip joint with an orthopedic prosthesis.
The use of a combination of treatments, usually coronary angioplasty and coronary artery bypass to reestablish patency in blocked arteries.
A combination of catheter ablation with thorascopic surgery to treat atrial fibrillation that is resistant to other treatments.
Heart conditions that are caused by high blood pressure, including coronary artery disease and heart failure.
Clinical evaluation of the utility of diagnostic procedures.
Injections of medication into the hypogastric plexus, which is a bundle of nerves near the bottom of the spinal cord. This will treat pain in the pelvic area.
Non-surgical treatment of Irritable Bowel Disease.
Therapy designed to use an individual's own immune system to recognize and destroy melanoma cancer cells.
Placement of a device that allows access to the epidural space of the spine for the delivery of pain medications.
A personalized therapeutic approach that takes a patient's lifestyle into account.
Angioplasty and stenting of the vessels of the neck and brain under fluoroscopy.
An infection in the gastrointestinal tract by a nematode.

Treatments to eliminate the need for intravenous nutritional support and restore diet and lifestyle for individuals with intestinal failure. Intestinal transplantation may treat irreversible intestinal failure.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic vascular disorder that affects the intestines.
A procedure in which a saline filled balloon is placed in the stomach to assist with weight loss.
For clinical decision-making, the purposeful and ongoing acquisition, interpretation, and synthesis of patient data obtained from clinical trials.
